  "response": "The sun appears to rise in the east and set in the west due to the Earth's rotation from west to east on its axis. This rotation makes it seem like the sun is moving across the sky, when in reality, it's the Earth that is spinning. Here's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. Earth rotates counterclockwise (when viewed from above the North Pole)\n2. This rotation causes the sun to appear to move from east to west\n3. The Earth's axis is tilted at about 23.5 degrees, which affects the exact path of the sun\n4. This east-west motion is consistent everywhere on Earth\n5. North and south are not rotational directions, so the sun would not naturally rise or set in those directions\n\nIf the Earth did not rotate, or rotated in a different direction, the sun's apparent movement across the sky would be different. The consistent east-to-west motion is a result of our planet's specific rotational characteristics.",
